In addition to the larger and more widespread differences of division into parts, order of subjects, and treatment of the additional matter, there are other variations of a minor character, especially those which are peculiar and individual to a particular manuscript. These help us to form rather an esti- mate of the worth of the manuscript, its relative goodness or badness as compared with the other copies than any definite idea as to its place in the family tree. In other words, there are none of the extemal or more special features of the early written texts which will give us anything more than a hazy notion as to how they are related to one another.
